{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at the module boundary: taxonomy data must survive request-building and handoff to the API client (\"request sent to the external API\"). A pure unit of a helper could miss wiring/serialization omissions. Rejected System because behavior does not require real network/OS; rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model output.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a fake in-process API client that records outbound payload; call classify with a taxonomy and assert the outbound request contains the full label set exactly once before dispatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.34,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic normalization/validation logic on returned data. The failure can be reproduced within one function/object boundary by feeding an out-of-taxonomy label. Rejected Integration because behavior text does not require real module handoff beyond supplying a raw label.","test_description":"Call normalization/response-mapping logic with taxonomy [legal, technical, financial, other] and raw label \"medical\"; assert final output is \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.79,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior explicitly targets normalization determinism for identical inputs; no I/O, no cross-module dependency required. Rejected higher levels because they add infrastructure unrelated to this failure mode.","test_description":"Invoke normalization repeatedly (or property-style) with the same raw response fixture and taxonomy; assert output label is identical across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.91,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires \"repeated live API calls\" and consistency of actual provider labels, which depends on real model behavior/non-determinism. A stub would hide this. Rejected Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N real provider calls for the same document/taxonomy under identical settings; record raw provider labels and module outputs; assert module label changes only when provider raw label changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.21,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is orchestration/order across request builder, budget policy, and dispatch gate (\"before dispatch\"). Unit tests of tokenizer math alone can miss accidental dispatch despite over-budget input. Rejected System because real network/OS is unnecessary; rejected Agentic because no dependence on model output content.","test_description":"Use in-process wiring with a spy/fake API client and configured budget; feed over-budget input and assert policy action (truncate or reject) occurs and dispatch behavior matches policy (blocked or adjusted) before client call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.61,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real AI provider response path and provider-reported usage metadata; mocks can trivially satisfy budget and miss real provider/tokenizer behavior. Per rule, real AI API execution defaults to Agentic unless only testing wrapper infrastructure; here the assertion is about actual provider usage.","test_description":"Execute real classification calls for representative documents with configured budget; assert provider-reported token usage fields are <= budget and flag any overages.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.64,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across client error handling, backoff/wait, and subsequent call outcome. In-process fakes can reproduce 429-like signals and verify retry behavior. Rejected System because real HTTP/network timing is not required by the behavior text; rejected Agentic because correctness is about control flow, not model judgment.","test_description":"Use a fake API client that returns rate-limit error then success; use controllable clock/sleeper; assert module waits per retry policy, retries, and returns success instead of surfacing the initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.08,"Ag